  "topic_name": "Human Body: Nervous System",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "The nervous system controls and coordinates body activities through electrical impulses. It consists of the central nervous system (CNS: brain and spinal cord) and peripheral nervous system (PNS: nerves). Neurons are the functional units, consisting of cell body, dendrites (receive impulses), and axon (transmit impulses). The brain has three main parts: cerebrum (thinking, memory, voluntary actions), cerebellum (balance, coordination), and medulla oblongata (involuntary functions like breathing, heartbeat). The spinal cord is protected by the vertebral column and controls reflex actions. Reflex arc components include receptor, sensory neuron, relay neuron, motor neuron, and effector. Sense organs (eye, ear) provide sensory input.",
    "rules": [
      "CNS consists of brain and spinal cord; PNS consists of nerves",
      "Neurons have cell body, dendrites (receive), and axon (transmit)",
      "Sensory neurons carry impulses to CNS; motor neurons carry from CNS",
      "Synapse is the junction between two neurons where neurotransmitters are released",
      "Cerebrum controls thinking, memory, and voluntary actions",
      "Cerebellum controls balance and coordination",
      "Medulla oblongata controls involuntary functions like breathing and heartbeat",
      "Reflex actions are quick, automatic, involuntary responses",
      "Reflex arc: receptor -> sensory neuron -> relay neuron -> motor neuron -> effector",
      "Eye defects: myopia (concave lens), hypermetropia (convex lens)"
    ]
  },
